            },
            "answerKey": {
              "assessmentType": "multiplechoice",
              "answers": {
                "answer_3": {
                  "score": 0.0,
                  "response": "Thanks to changing work rules and mechanization, many Americans enjoyed more leisure time. The average workweek for manufacturing laborers fell from 60 hours in 1890 to 51 in 1920. By the early 1900s, white-collar workers might spend only 8 to 10 hours a day at work and a half day on Saturday."
